 in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mandeville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Gabrielle, Camille, Emile, Fernand, Fernande, Gaston, Jean-Paul, Lucien, Michel.","French: habitational name from Mandeville, the name of two places in Normandy, derived from Latin <i>magna villa</i> ‘large estate’, or a variant of <b>Manneville</b>, a habitational name from Manneville, the name of several places in Normandy (see 2 below). Compare   Montville   and   Monville  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Manneville (Seine-Maritime, Calvados), Manneville-sur-Risle (Eure), or Magneville (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mansfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place so named in Nottinghamshire. The placename means ‘open land by the river Maun’, from the river name Maun (which may take its name from a hill named with Old English <i>mamme</i> ‘teat’) + Old English <i>feld</i> ‘open country’.","Irish (Waterford): when not an importation of 1, this is an altered form of the Norman name <b>de Manville</b> (see   Mandeville   3).","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Mansfeld</b>, a habitational name from a place so called in Saxony."]},{"name":"Manderville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manwell","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manville","meanings":["English (Sussex and Lancashire): variant of   Mandeville  .","Altered form of   Mainville   1, a surname of Swiss French origin (see   Miville  ).","French: variant of <b>Menville</b>, a habitational name from Menville in Haute-Garonne, and also of   Mainville   2."]},{"name":"Mundell","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  .","Americanized form of German <b>Mündel</b> (or some other similar, like-sounding surname): nickname for someone with a prominent mouth, from Middle High German <i>munt</i>, <i>mündelīn</i> ‘(little) mouth’."]},{"name":"Monville","meanings":["Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","Walloon: habitational name from Monville in Namur province in Wallonia (Belgium), of the same etymology as in 3 below.","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Montville in Seine-Maritime or Monville in Calvados, both named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’."]},{"name":"Mandal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Chandi, Sanjay, Sankar, Somnath, Aditi, Aditya, Ajit, Amala, Amitabha, Anil, Anirudh, Aparna.","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>maṇḍala</i>, a word that has several meanings, including ‘sphere’ and ‘halo’.","English (Cumbria; of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Montville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Vernice.","Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","French: variant of   Monville  . This surname is very rare in France, found mainly in Creuse."]},{"name":"Manfull","meanings":["English (Midlands): probably a variant of   Mandeville  . Compare   Manville  ."]}]},{"name":"Annora","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Andrew</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"Agnes\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Annora \"Agnes\" de Mandeville was born in 1120, in Devon, England. She married Robert FitzWilliam de Cardinham in United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1169, in Cardinham, Cornwall, England."},"et":{"1120–after 1169":"1120–pärast 1169","1115–1177":"1115–1177","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1120–1169":"1120–1169","1115":"1115","1169":"1169","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","after 1169":"pärast 1169","Cardinham, Cornwall, England":"Cardinham, Cornwall, England","United Kingdom":"United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Bodmin, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1120–after 1169":"1120–1169 jälkeen","1115–1177":"1115–1177","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1120–1169":"1120–1169","1115":"1115","1169":"1169","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","after 1169":"1169 jälkeen","Cardinham, Cornwall, England":"Cardinham, Cornwall, England","United Kingdom":"Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Bodmin, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1120–after 1169":"1120–après 1169","1115–1177":"1115–1177","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1120–1169":"1120–1169","1115":"1115","1169":"1169","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","after 1169":"après 1169","Cardinham, Cornwall, England":"Cardinham, Cornouailles, Angleterre","United Kingdom":"Royaume-Uni","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Bodmin, Cornouailles, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Annora \"Agnes\" de Mandeville est née en 1120, à Devon, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Robert FitzWilli